reviews_data.review_text: Beautiful setting, great trails, a gardeners paradise full of inspiration. Well worth the trip.
Absolutely beautiful! Great for kids. There were so many butterflies and bees! Bring water! They do have a store you can buy some at.

It's a nice cool big garden, a nice place to walk and if you're a nature photographer this is the perfect place to take pictures, and if you have kids this is a nice place to take them to walk, play, and look at the beautiful gardens
Great place to adventure and wonderful for the kids
Wonderful Garden. Highly Recommend!
Great place to wear out your kids
Beautiful even in the winter time. Wonderful place to go on a date. Their inside portion has a wide variety of botanicals. We will also sometimes ride our bikes here.
The membership is definitely worth it if you have a family that enjoys hiking and nature. Excited for the castle park coming soon...
Beautiful location for a wedding
A wonderful place to relax.  The atmosphere is wonderful!
Jazz in the garden was a vibe.  Totally enjoyed it.
A beautiful place to take a walk,very stroller friendly👍🌸We saw so many butterflies at this visit 🦋 Kids are fascinated by all the beautiful fountains 💦
Super friendly staff. Beautiful garden which is perfect for a summer walk.  Looking forward to the Christmas light show
I love the gardens! There is an amazing glass conservatory with exotic plants and succulents. Miles of trails behind the gardens.
Petal To The Medal had a wonderful time
Absolutely wonderful. My GoPro caught all of this beautiful greenery. Perfect place for the kids as well.

What a beautiful place for a walk! First we visited the butterfly bungalow, and saw lots of them. Biologists were there to chat and answer questions. Then we walked the gardens. There are lots of pathways, water features, and a new trail with areas for kids to play creatively such as a small creek, a place to make music using natural materials, and places to let their imagination go. A huge castle is being built that looks like it will be a great play structure. There are trails and pathways throughout the property, and you can walk as far (or not) as you like. Trails outside the garden are free. There’s also a cafe with a small gift shop inside the garden, and a store at the front entrance that we didn’t visit, but the website says they have coffee, sandwiches, snacks, etc.
Beautiful

Went in May, came back in July. It was a delight to see how things had grown in, different things are blooming, etc. The garden is big enough that I've still not seen all of it. There are enough shady spots to take a break in and have a picnic that we didn't overheat. When you go, don't miss the orchid conservatory!
Awesome place to spend a few hours. I'm happy I took the drive from Charlotte to visit.
Right now, the live butterfly exhibit is going on. The grounds are gorgeous.
Really enjoy the space.  Butterfly bungalow was a hit with the kids.  Lots of pathways to walk.  Not a ton of shade in many paths.

Absolutely fantastic place.  Plants are beautiful place was well maintained the greenhouse was amazing.  I hope the get the money to finish the back castle section. That would absolutely send it over the top.  Great place to hang out for not much money.

A stunning and serene escape. Daniel Stowe Botanical Garden offers beautifully designed landscapes, walking paths, fountains, and a lush conservatory filled with orchids and tropical plants. Great for families, couples, or solo visits. Every season brings something new. A botanical treasure near Charlotte.
Peaceful

Absolutely stunning gardens, canal, pergolas, conservatory, and grounds... I've been to my fair share of botanical gardens and greenhouses and I was really wowed by this place. My highlight was the conservatory; the plants were huge, full, happy, and thriving — extending all the way to ceiling — and the water features added a lot to the ambiance and overall magic. The canal area is also gorgeously adorned with both flowers and tasteful sculptures. I spotted so many huge butterflies (and caterpillars!) while I was here, both in the enclosure and free roaming. This is a gorgeous place to experience natural beauty, and I can't wait to return!

Decent price for the family of all ages.

I recommend the family pass if you live within Charlotte or the surrounding area.  The family pass can be used at other botanical gardens across the country i was told.  Plus it is good for all members of a household.

The gardens are beautiful and there is even a butterfly garden where you can witness numerous different kinds of butterfly's in a natural habitat.  This is great for kids of all ages!

There are plenty of trails for walking, or even cycling.

Lots to do here and see.

Stop by there gift shop or cafe on the way out for a beverage or even a gift.
Beautiful visit! The grounds are lovely. The butterfly conservatory is very small but was a good experience.

The original portion of the garden is lovely! The butterflies and bumblebees throughout the pollinator garden were interesting and captivating!
When this garden originally opened they had an open shuttle tram to bring guest back to the front of the garden near the Orchid conservatory. I hope they will extend the garden with lush flowers and fountains on the opposite side of this drive, with additional brick pathways so that guest can naturally loop  back through to the entrance!
Beautiful! Highly Recommend!!!

Plant nerds paradise! This place is pretty big so be prepared to be in the sun and do a ton if walking if you want to see the entire property. It has plenty of parking, drinks and snacks. $20 to get in which is kind of high to look at plants but I can see how this place would need the money to maintain it. Gosh its massive. I'm glad places like this exists but in realty it's a one time visit for me. It's still 5 stars for what it is though!
Peaceful spot

Today was the right time to visit the butterfly bungalow.
There weren't many orchids.
I think it's a little bit expensive but it's nice.
Went there for the Christmas lights last year.  It was amazing!  Had music coordinated with the light show.  Had a great time.

These are gorgeous botanical gardens! I've lived in Charlotte for a couple of years and only recently heard of Daniel Stowe. Now that I have seen the greenhouse, butterfly exhibit, water features, pathways and abundant floral scenery I will be sure to come back regularly.
Tracy Smith is absolutely wonderful!  Highly recommend. Just beautiful to visit.

Beautiful and creative walking paths among lovely exotic and natural plantings
Small gift shop and café inside main building.  There was an ice  ream/sorbet/gèlatto truck on site as well.  I had hoped for more of a gift shop,as I had been to the NY BOTANICAL GARDENS and LONGWOOÐ GARDENS in PA, but it is  small and  quite nice.
Great place to visit. Beautifully landscaped and trails(in development) hold much promise for the future.
Beautiful gardens!  It is such a joy to visit and spend the day enjoying nature. 🦋🌻🪻 Lots of fun for all ages. 🪹 🐢🐦
1st timer … it was Beautiful..‼️🌺💐🌸🌻.. so many things to do here … splash pad .. and play area … (the castle play ground not finished yet )… trails .. just amazed .. what a great afternoon..!!

This is one of my favorite places in the Charlotte area to visit. The gardens are always so beautiful and the building itself is very exquisite. The perfect place to go for a quiet and peaceful day. Their shop always has some beautiful finds

We enjoy going as something different to do but have learned to expect that most areas  are not well kept (even in spring). Today there were plenty of areas that looked depressing, empty and uncared for as well as many empty fountains. We saw trash on benches and scattered around.  It’s expensive for how it’s maintained & for what they currently have to see. You might enjoy a park elsewhere for free considering the garden charges for visits.  Definitely manage your expectations if you go. Idea- call ahead and ask what gardens are blooming or being redone. It definitely seems like they don’t have staff or money to maintain the property.

Between cute stores out front and an arrangement of events to choose from throughout the year, this place has something for everyone. Walk and sip as you enjoy some of the most serene environments the Carolinas has to offer in one space. Great place for families to spend a day or a walk with a date, don't miss the green house or the butterfly garden!
This place is gorgeous
Beautiful gardens! Had a wonderful day walking the gardens with my sister and niece. My favorite was the butterfly enclosure. Very warm day I'd like to go again maybe on a cooler day

Además en primavera están las flores en su esplendor lo que es muy hermoso. Beautiful....wear good shoes!!

We had a highly enjoyable experience at the Stowe Conservancy as we strolled through the gardens and took in the beauty of the flowers and plants of all varieties.  There is plenty of information posted to help you understand what you’re looking at and lots of opportunities for children to play so they don’t get bored.  The water features are delightful and the walking trails are extremely well maintained.  This is a great way to spend time enjoying nature in a relaxing, peaceful environment.
Love Daniel Stowe with the family. The Butterfly Bungalow is such an amazing addition.
The Gardens were beautiful. My favorite was the Orchard Green House.
A great place to visit with Nature Trails. Orchids. Butterfly Bungalow. Farm Store, Dog Park!
Quiet, beautiful, verdant. Beautifully manicured paths and gardens. Take in all of nature with a relaxing walk through the flowers.

Only a few sections were interesting, most of the land is undeveloped open prairie as they designated it. The glass house of orchids was very interesting. Long and slow moving lines to enter the Butterfly Bungalow, not worth it.
Lovely visit gardens are beautiful for Spring. We enjoyed walking in them and loved the kid play area as well.
The butterfly festival was well worth the trip to Belmont and the gardens are gorgeous

She felt so comfortable to walk around and rest when needed, and anywhere there are steps, there is a ramp too. The grounds are beautiful. It was a perfect day.
This place was beautiful  and tranquil well worth the trip.

A beautiful place for engagement photos, or wedding ceremony! As a NC wedding photographer, I enjoy coming here to take photos! Beautiful garden area with plenty of diverse plants and I absolutely love the greenhouse!

We have enjoyed this lovely garden during Spring, Summer and now Autumn— each season holds new surprises. I love that the garden sets up vignettes for family photos too. Very thoughtful. I look forward to seeing this in the winter. Camellias are just blooming, azaleas are in bloom and it’s amazing how much color the garden has despite cooler temps.
Hermoso Lugar muchas flores y lugares para pasar un día maravilloso

Visited in May, gardens were underwhelming.  More weeds than I expected for an informal garden.  The lost trail was very well maintained and shady, with a wide stone path and fun things for kids to do like splashing in a rock garden stream.

This place was amazing. There are so many beautiful and exotic plants. I didn't have enough time to go on the nature trails, but I saw a lot of things there. The orchid place was really pretty and it was like a rainforest in there. I love ferns, so I was really happy that I saw so many. This place also helped me pick out my mom's Mother's Day present. I learned that she does not like marigolds, but she loves red flowers. (I ended up getting her fuchsias.) They have a small ice cream stand, and I really like the mango flavor. In the building that you pay, there is a lot of beautiful art and photography. My favorite part was definitely the sprinkler part that I ran through multiple times 😆. It had pretty scenery, and it was very entertaining, lol. Their shops were also very cool. I saw a lot of Bigfoot and sasquach things that I was very happy about. Although I wish there were more criptyd stuff like mothman or wendigos. I loved the sitting rooms in both of the stores. They were very cozy and made me happy. Overall, I rated this place 5 stars. You should definitely check it out. (Super off-topic, but if you put sweet potatoes chopped up with taco seasoning in the airfryer, it is a good healthy snack, hehe)
Beautiful place with a decent selection of plants. Something  for everyone.

It is a shame what this new administration has done with the wonderful garden it was one day. I have been a member of the garden for about 15 years. After year 2020, everything changed dramatically. They are putting more concrete instead of plants and flowers. They are leaving the walking paths in the garden as gravel paths. If you are a wheelchair user you will be in trouble to pass by the first section, before the long fountain garden. It is becoming a bar instead of a garden. No more photography contest, well, there is very poor nature for a photo contest which I have the pleasure of winning the first place in one category back in 2018. I do not know if I should feel bad or glad about Mr. Daniel Stowe and Wife: bad for not having them around us, or glad because they are not seeing the destruction of their work and passion. If you want to walk on the trails or drink alcohol, this is your place. If you want to enjoy a garden, go somewhere else. Ah, and if you need that electronic button to open the door on your way out, ask for assistance to open the heavy door because the button never works.

Beautiful wedding venue!
This place is absolutely breathtaking! There are plenty of beautiful arrangements, and the conservatory is amazing!

Not sure why they took down my review as others need to be aware. I booked multiple tickets to the Christmas lights in 2023. Daniel Stowe closed due to cold temperatures (above freezing still). They then refused to refund me. All they would offer is to let me use the tickets at a later date, but my family was only in town for a couple nights and the other days were booked. The manager was extremely rude and would not budge. I ended up having to dispute the charge through my credit card company and finally got my money back. This is a greedy corporation that is focused on money and not customer experience.

I really enjoyed attending the sustainability swap in April 2025. It was well attended and expertly organized. I appreciated the swap as a way to meet other members, share treasures and give to charity. A nice touch was the small bar and as always a beautiful walk through the gardens. Thank you!
My son had his wedding there.
If you are a plant and flower lover then must visit. Kids and adults will love it. The butterfly place was cute. Overall amazing

I've visited this garden almost every year since it opened. The garden used to be beautiful and well-kept, with flowers and shrubs blooming every season. It's now a weedy mess, with few flowers, and dead or dying shrubs and trees. There have been some improvements to the natural area outside the "garden" and new paths added inside, but the actual flowering garden is completely neglected. It's so sad to see the deterioration from what it once was.

Update 04/13/25.
The garden looks even worse than in  2023 and 2024. The beds are filled with weeds and poorly maintained shrubs. A big new playground project is in the works - but the most basic garden care is neglected. It's  depressing to walk through this sad, neglected mess.

We love Daniel Stowe Botanical Garden. We have been regular members since around 2012, with breaks here and there. They have absolutely come a long ways since the beginning of our time with them. We love them so much we decided to marry there in 2021 and it was everything I could have ever dreamed of. I'm excited to see how the partnership with Gaston Day School goes, considering this is my son's first year at the school and the one thing I had wish before they announced this partnering was how I wanted him to have access to more nature themed education. This announcement made me wholeheartedly happy. We're excited to return and explore all the new programs, events, and of course, the gardens.

Visited on September 19, 2024.  Horribly disappointed.  The garden is so poorly maintained it felt like it was about to be closed.  I would say perhaps 75% of the garden was not weeded - and the weeds in many areas were larger than the specimen plants.  This was made more surprising by the fact that the botanical garden isn't even that large... I could have probably weeded it myself in less than a week.  Many of the weeds had clearly been there all summer.  Inside the orchid house someone was doing some minor plant work, and the green waste was scattered around on the concrete walk - like the person couldn't be bothered to carry a bucket with them.  Trees and bushes poorly maintained - some had been planted too closely together and had died back, and the dead tree had been removed - leaving a stump and a huge hole in the landscape.  Visible rust on iron work in many places.  Chipped/old paint.  Who manages their volunteer groups?  Do they have any?  I was so shocked I even went to their web site to check their staff - and they seem to have a full time staff of 10 horticulturalists.  Do they walk the grounds?  My daughter had recommended the visit and spent the entire time apologizing.

This place exceeded my expectations and I'm still overjoyed after seeing a lush green and colorful array of flora as if Persephone herself was there tending the land. Walking through the Pergola's onto the succession of spectacular gardens, I was in complete wonderment. The Canal Garden was overflowing with fragrant blossoms and foxgloves lined the pathway as water features and fountains unfolded along the way. I admired an abundance of wonderful plants and sculptures strategically placed throughout in a vivid design. To my surprise, I noticed many plant species that I had never heard of or seen before, forever learning something new. The Orchid Conservatory with the waterfall wall was amazing. (I've always admired glass garden conservatories like the ones found in the US Botanical Garden in DC, Vizcaya Museum in Miami and Isabell Stewart Gardner Museum in Boston.) And if you are an orchid and tropical plant lover, as I am, the conservatory is a must see. The White Garden reminded me of a secret English garden tucked away for tranquility. The children's area called, Lost Hollow, was crazy good. They had a mini amphitheater that reminded me of my visit to Ephesus last year where a reenactment of Cleopatra and Ceasar (or Mark Antony) was held. The childrens area also had a magical/enchanted Fae/Faery like area where you can play in little forest dwellings and king and queen stone carved throne chairs with views of walking trails below. There is so much to see and do here. You can't get bored here. There is so much to learn and explore or just unwind or have a romantic outing. In comparison to my favorite garden, Dallas Arboretum & Garden, I love North Carolina's tree-lined landscape that added a wilderness and untamed backdrop to the garden, giving it a balanced elegantly manicured but not overly groomed appeal. Sometimes it's attractive to be slightly wild and rough around the edges, checkout the wildflowers in the prairie area. As a bonus, this place offers garden classes and workshops, summer camps for children, opportunities for private events, and has two stores (including a gift shop). Special thank you to the lady who welcomed me in and explained the map and noticed I might do a little work and pointed out great shaded spots for working. (She lovingly expressed for me not to work too hard...much appreciated.) Many thanks to the Boards, donors, and staff for the great work here.

Disappointing Visit to Daniel Stowe Botanical Gardens

Where were the flowers? My recent trip to Daniel Stowe Botanical Gardens was a major letdown. Instead of vibrant blooms and manicured landscapes, we were greeted by a disappointing display of neglect.

Overgrown and Unkempt:  Weeds ran rampant throughout the gardens, choking out any semblance of flowers or well-maintained plant life. Dead plants hung limply, and the whole place had a neglected feel.  The sight of a large blacksnake slithering amongst the weeds only added to the unsettling atmosphere.

Water Woes: The ponds, what should have been a beautiful focal point, were covered in a thick layer of algae.  The presence of dead mice and frogs floating on the surface was not exactly picturesque.

Underwhelming Exhibit:  The "exhibit" was a total dud. It felt more like a high school student's hastily thrown together extra credit project, and not one that deserved any praise.

Pricey Neglect:  Charging an admission fee, especially the hefty $14.95 per person, is outrageous considering the state of the gardens.   Being overcharged for an extra person only added insult to injury.

Save your money and your time!  Skip Daniel Stowe Botanical Gardens until they get their act together. There are plenty of other places where you can enjoy beautiful, well-maintained gardens for a fraction of the price.

Visiting Daniel Stowe Botanical Gardens yesterday, March 26 2024, from Central Florida, I was really excited to see the gardens.  Listed as number 8 of things to do in Charlotte, posted by travel us news, I couldn’t wait to visit. What a shock! Instead of seeing beautiful orchids, flowers, plants, etc. I saw a lot of dead, overgrown, under watered and unkempt gardens! Unfortunately, the weeds have taken over everywhere! Dead branches were hanging loosely in trees. The Wings Exhibit was closed and didn’t show any signs of opening anytime soon. A mound of mulch waiting to be spread. There were a couple of employees, one riding on a tractor and the other riding on a cart. However, I never saw anyone tending to the gardens. The employee at the front door, who was working the cash register, was nice.

Not sure if it’s a lack of employees. However, I would think management would do something about these unloved gardens! At this time, I’m sorry that I wasted my money and time to visit DSBG!

Something truly special and stunningly majestic! This place exceeded my expectations and I'm still overjoyed after seeing a lush green and colorful array of flora as if Persephone herself was there tending the land. Walking through the Pergola's onto the succession of spectacular gardens, I was in complete wonderment. The Canal Garden was overflowing with fragrant blossoms and foxgloves lined the pathway as water features and fountains unfolded along the way. I admired an abundance of wonderful plants and sculptures strategically placed throughout in a vivid design. To my surprise, I noticed many plant species that I had never heard of or seen before, forever learning something new. The Orchid Conservatory with the waterfall wall was amazing. (I've always admired glass garden conservatories like the ones found in the US Botanical Garden in DC, Vizcaya Museum in Miami and Isabell Stewart Gardner Museum in Boston.) And if you are an orchid and tropical plant lover, as I am, the conservatory is a must see. The White Garden reminded me of a secret English garden tucked away for tranquility. The children's area called, Lost Hollow, was crazy good. They had a mini amphitheater that reminded me of my visit to Ephesus last year where a reenactment of Cleopatra and Ceasar (or Mark Antony) was held. The childrens area also had a magical/enchanted Fae/Faery like area where you can play in little forest dwellings and king and queen stone carved throne chairs with views of walking trails below. There is so much to see and do here. You can't get bored here. There is so much to learn and explore or just unwind or have a romantic outing. In comparison to my favorite garden, Dallas Arboretum & Garden, I love North Carolina's tree-lined landscape that added a wilderness and untamed backdrop to the garden, giving it a balanced elegantly manicured but not overly groomed appeal. Sometimes it's attractive to be slightly wild and rough around the edges, checkout the wildflowers in the prairie area. As a bonus, this place offers garden classes and workshops, summer camps for children, opportunities for private events, and has two stores (including a gift shop). Special thank you to the lady who welcomed me in and explained the map and noticed I might do a little work and pointed out great shaded spots for working. (She lovingly expressed for me not to work too hard...much appreciated.) Many thanks to the Boards, donors, and staff for the great work here.

Disappointing Visit to Daniel Stowe Botanical Gardens

Where were the flowers? My recent trip to Daniel Stowe Botanical Gardens was a major letdown. Instead of vibrant blooms and manicured landscapes, we were greeted by a disappointing display of neglect.

Overgrown and Unkempt:  Weeds ran rampant throughout the gardens, choking out any semblance of flowers or well-maintained plant life. Dead plants hung limply, and the whole place had a neglected feel.  The sight of a large blacksnake slithering amongst the weeds only added to the unsettling atmosphere.

Water Woes: The ponds, what should have been a beautiful focal point, were covered in a thick layer of algae.  The presence of dead mice and frogs floating on the surface was not exactly picturesque.

Underwhelming Exhibit:  The "exhibit" was a total dud. It felt more like a high school student's hastily thrown together extra credit project, and not one that deserved any praise.

Pricey Neglect:  Charging an admission fee, especially the hefty $14.95 per person, is outrageous considering the state of the gardens.   Being overcharged for an extra person only added insult to injury.

Save your money and your time!  Skip Daniel Stowe Botanical Gardens until they get their act together. There are plenty of other places where you can enjoy beautiful, well-maintained gardens for a fraction of the price.

There were a couple of employees, one riding on a tractor and the other riding on a cart. However, I never saw anyone tending to the gardens. The employee at the front door, who was working the cash register, was nice.

Not sure if it’s a lack of employees. However, I would think management would do something about these unloved gardens! At this time, I’m sorry that I wasted my money and time to visit DSBG!
